# Solution \#2

### Simple Solution with **O(2n)** Time complexity and **O(n)** Space.

- Use a Set to store all the values as you iterate through the LinkedList
- Iterate through the set again to now store the unique values back into a new LinkedList
- **NOTE:** _For some reason, had to use **insertAtTail** to properly store the data_

```javascript
/**
* Access HeadNode => list.getHead()
* Access Length => list.length;
* Check if list is empty => list.isEmpty()
* Insert at head => list.insertAtHead(value)
* Delete at head => list.deleteAtHead()
* Insert at tail => list.insertAtTail(value)
* Search for element => list.search(value)
* Delete by value => list.deleteVal(value)
* Node class { data ; Node nextElement;}
*/
function removeDuplicates(list) {
  // Edge case: check if the list is empty
  if (list.isEmpty()) return null;
  // create a set data-structure to store the results 
  const uniqueItems = new Set();
  let currNode = list.getHead().nextElement;
  while(currNode) {    
    uniqueItems.add(currNode.data);
    currNode = currNode.nextElement;
  }

  // now that the results are stored, iterate through the set to get unique values
  // store those results into a new LinkedList
  const result = Array.from(uniqueItems);  
  let newList = new LinkedList();
  for (let val of result) {    
    newList.insertAtTail(val);
  }
  return newList; //return the updated list here
}
```

