- Node JS runs in a single process and is basically in one thread.
- This means that it does not utilize all the CPUs on a host.
- To remedy this, Node JS has a **cluster** module.

## Cluster Module
- Under the hood, Node JS then uses interprocess communication to distribute the load between the chart processes, round robin way.
- Cluster module is built into Node core package.

```javascript
const cluster = require('cluster');
...
// if the CPU process is the master process ..do something
if(cluster.isMaster) {
 log.info(`Master ${process.pid} is running`);
 for (let i= 0; i < numCPUs; i++) { 
   cluster.fork();
 }
 cluster.on('exit', (worker) => {
  log.fatal(`Worker ${worker.process.pid} just died`);
 });

} else {
 ...// do your app logic here !!
}
```

## PM2 Module

- Node cluster is not the only way to achieve this.
- We can use the process manager 2 module to scale up all CPUs as well
- Unlike `cluster` and `os` module which are built into Node. **PM2** module is external and needs to be installed.

