- The Controller annotated with the `@Controller('serviceName')` annotation which takes in a string parameter - name of the handler

```javascript
import { Controller, Get, Post, Body } from '@nestjs/common';
import { TasksService } from './tasks.service';
import { Task } from './tasks.model';

@Controller('tasks')
export class TasksController {

    constructor(private taskService: TasksService) {}

    @Get()
    getAllTasks(): Task[] {
        return this.taskService.getAllTasks();
    }

    @Post()
    createTask ( @Body() body ) {
        console.log('Body is: ', body);
    }
}
```

- For processing the Request body we can either 

- Use the Entire Request Body as follows

```javascript
@Post()
    createTask ( @Body() body ) {
        console.log('Body payload entire object is: ', body);
    }
```

- Or we can specifically look for fields within the Body payload. Like so

```javascript
@Post()
    createTask ( 
          @Body('title') title: string,
          @Body('description') description: string,
    ) {
        console.log('Title is: ', title);
        console.log('Description is: ', description);
    }
```

- The second method is a better suited design as it helps in error handling.

# Services

The `@Injectable` decorator is used for the following purpose:

- It is used to define that a certain class should have shared instance across the module.
- The instance can be then injected using Dependency Injection
- All injectors (controllers) will have access to the same shared instance and its state

### Difference between Service and Injectable

- Injectable is used to share the instance of the class across the module
- Service is a layer that provides some sort of Business Logic.

```javascript
import { Injectable } from '@nestjs/common';
import { Task, TaskStatus } from './tasks.model';
import * as uuid from 'uuid/v1';

@Injectable()
export class TasksService {

    private tasks: Task[];

    getAllTasks(): Task[] {
        return this.tasks;
    }

    createTask (title: string, description: string): Task {
        const task: Task = {
            id: uuid(),
            title,
            description,
            status: TaskStatus.OPEN
        };

        this.tasks.push(task);
        return task;
    }

}
```

# Answer

## Pain Point

- We do not have a unified way to pass objects between Controllers and Services for arguments.
- Every time we need to introduce a new parameter to the Web-Service, maintenance becomes hard.


---

## Data Transfer Objects

A Data Transfer Object is an object which carries data between processes. 
- It encapsulates data and sends it from one subsystem of an application to another.
- It defines how data will be sent over the network
- More bulletproof code
- Used for for storage, retrieval, serialization, deserialization of data.

A Data Transfer Object (dto) is different from a model as it only defines the shape of an object **for a specific transaction / service** not the entire Model / Schema

- It can be an interface / abstract class.
- The recommended approach in Nest JS is to use classes to define a Data Transfer Object (dto).
- The reason being, interface are specifically part of Typescript, and will not be preserved post-compilation
- Classes on the other hand, are Ecmascript specification which can exist even after Typescript compilation.
- Nest JS cannot refer to the interfaces at runtime, but can easily refer to classes.

---

## Example of a DTO

The following is how you specify a Data Transfer Object

### DTO

```javascript
export class CreateTasksDto {
    title: string;
    description: string;
};
```

This Create Task DTO can now be used to define the POST parameters in a controller, like so:

### Controller

```javascript
@Controller('tasks')
export class TasksController {

    constructor(private taskService: TasksService) {}
...
...
...
// DTO being used as parameter type definition
 @Post()
    createTask ( @Body() createTask: CreateTasksDto ): Task {
        return this.taskService.createTask(createTask);
    }
...
}
```

This can now be referred in a Service, like so:

### Service

```javascript
import { Injectable } from '@nestjs/common';
import { Task, TaskStatus } from '../models/tasks.model';
import * as uuid from 'uuid/v1';
import { CreateTasksDto } from '../dto/tasks.dto';

@Injectable()
export class TasksService {
...
...
...
// DTO being used as a request param type definition
createTask (createTask: CreateTasksDto): Task {
        const { title, description } = createTask;
        const task: Task = {
            id: uuid(),
            title,
            description,
            status: TaskStatus.OPEN
        };
        this.tasks.push(task);
        return task;
    }
}
```

