# 1. Functional Component using Type

To declare a Typescript functional component, We first write what datatypes to the our `props` we need to pass.

The below code how to use `Type` keyword to define our custom props. Later we will implement the same component using `Interface` keyword

```javascript
type ISelectOption = {
    title: string,
    onClick:(evt: any) => void
};
```

We are using the `type` keyword to derive our proptypes.

Our Functional Component is then declared as follows:

```javascript
/**
 * Reusable Rounded Button Component
 */
import React, { FunctionComponent } from 'react';

type ISelectOption = {
    title: string,
    onClick:(evt: any) => void
};

/**
 * Reusable Rounded Button Component
 */
import React, { FunctionComponent } from 'react';

type ISelectOption = {
    title: string,
    onClick:(evt: any) => void
};

const RoundedButton: FunctionComponent<ISelectOption> = (props): JSX.Element => {
    return (
        <React.Fragment>
            <button onClick={props.onClick}
                    className="md:mt-6 
                    outline-none 
                    focus:outline-none 
                    hover:bg-indigo-100 
                    self-end 
                    flex mx-auto 
                    lg:mx-0 
                    bg-white 
                    text-gray-800 
                    font-bold 
                    rounded-full 
                    my-2 
                    py-2 
                    px-8 
                    shadow 
                    opacity-75">{props.title}</button>
        </React.Fragment>
    );
};

export default RoundedButton;
```

---

# 2. Functional Component using an Interface

The same Rounded Button can be declared using an `Interface` as shown below. This also works in React:

```javascript
/**
 * Reusable Rounded Button Component
 */
import React, { FunctionComponent } from 'react';

interface ISelectOption {
    title: string,
    onClick:(evt: any) => void
};

const RoundedButton = (props: ISelectOption): JSX.Element => {
    return (
        <React.Fragment>
            <button onClick={props.onClick}
                    className="md:mt-6 
                    outline-none 
                    focus:outline-none 
                    hover:bg-indigo-100 
                    self-end 
                    flex mx-auto 
                    lg:mx-0 
                    bg-white 
                    text-gray-800 
                    font-bold 
                    rounded-full 
                    my-2 
                    py-2 
                    px-8 
                    shadow 
                    opacity-75">{props.title}</button>
        </React.Fragment>
    );
};

export default RoundedButton;
```

---

# What's the difference ?

- Its more of a choice of preference than a comparison on which is best. Typescript respects both `Type` or `Interface` declaration. Also important to note that both these keywords are Typescript specific. ie., they dont exist post compilation.

- **NOTE:** If you want to use the datatype `FunctionComponent` then you must pass the interface / type as a `generic` to the FunctionComponent. like so:

```javascript
// If datatyping FunctionComponent, pass the interface / type as generic
const RoundedButton: FunctionComponent<ISelectOption> = (props): JSX.Element => {
...
}
```

The below code will throw an error, As React assums that your `FunctionComponent` has a `void` return type:

```javascript
// This throws an error
const RoundedButton: FunctionComponent = (props: ISelectOption): JSX.Element => {
....
}
```

